what works:
    - checkpointing a program with ./ckpt <executable>
    - reading a checkpoint image file with ./readckpt ckpt.dat

brief descriptions:
    ckpt.c:
        - preloads libckpt.so with setenv("LD_PRELOAD", ...)
        - calls execvp() to execute the program passed into argv
    libckpt.c:
        - uses a constructor function that registers a signal handler
          for SIGUSR2
        - saves info about each segment from /proc/self/maps into an array
          of structs (ckpt_header_t)
        - saves a final ckpt_header_t with is_reg_context=1 and 
          data_size=sizeof(ucontext_t) to head the ucontext_t data
        - writes each header and data pair to a checkpoint image file
          (ckpt.dat) in the format HEADER1, DATA1, HEADER2, DATA2, ...;
          the header is the data of a ckpt_header_t; the data is the data
          at the memory region between start and end if is_reg_context=0, or 
          the data of a ucontext_t (from getcontext()) if is_reg_context=1
    readckpt.c:
        - reads the info of each ckpt_header_t from the checkpoint image file
          (named ckpt.dat)
        - prints the start and end address, permissions (rwxp), filename,
          value of is_reg_context, and data_size for each checkpoint header
        - prints the value of each general register saved in the ucontext_t
          data section of the checkpoint image file (in uc_mcontext.gregs)

makefile usage:
    - make build: builds all executables and libckpt.so
    - make clean: removes all executables, libckpt.so and ckpt.dat
    - make check: checkpoints a program and uses ./readckpt ckpt.dat to
                  print out information about the checkpointed process
